      "writtenOn": "2020-10-23T21:40:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This comment took me a long time to parse because there\u0027s a lot going on. Here\u0027s my take. Did I get it?\n\n`stmt` is a sub-statement that was extracted from the original Statement referenced by this Node, or a Nop. (Or a null? Not sure, but we\u0027ve got new null checks.)\n\nBy the time you call `setStatement`, `stmt` is no longer actually a part of the existing statement held by the Node--the caller has decided to move it out, so that node will hold a null.\n\nIt\u0027s assumed that `usage` starts with all of the references in the Node\u0027s statement accounted for. However, the caller has stolen away the portion of that statement that they want to keep, but has not updated the usage bookkeeping to match. So we update the usage bookkeeping here, by walking the Node\u0027s statement in its current form and subtracting out references. This works because we\u0027ve already moved out the sub-statement that we want to keep (or we want to keep none of it, and we\u0027re replacing with a Nop or a null). Then we replace the Node\u0027s statement with the newly supplied statement.",
